Learning a New Language

Name: Tsewang Thilly

Learning a new language is hard! And it is harder to decide how, when everyone has thier own theory on best way to learn a new language. Through machine learning I decide to test and improve one approch. Stuart Webb, professor of applied linguistics at the University of Western Ontario, claims that "if you learn only 800 of the most frequently-used lemmas in English, you'll be able to understand 75% of the language as it is spoken in normal life."

link to the article

800 lemma is not that of a challange, (800/365 = 2.19 words) learning 2 lemma a day for a year, and you can understand 75% of a new language.

#getting most common 800 words in English
url = "https://1000mostcommonwords.com/1000-most-common-english-words/"
page = req(url) 
page_html = page.read()
page.close()
page_s = soup(page_html, "html.parser")
tbl = page_s.findAll("div",{"class":"entry-content"})
t = tbl[0].findAll('tr')


data = []
for v in t[1:]:
    for l in v.findAll('td')[2:]:
        data.append(l.text.replace("’","'"))
data[0] = data[0].lower()
data = np.char.lower(data)
data.sort()

#scappring words within the comments of different youtube categories such as finance, health, education, entertainment
#below how to scrap youtube comments
#link https://github.com/dddat1017/Scraping-Youtube-Comments
def scrape(url):
    
    """
    Extracts the comments from the Youtube video given by the URL.
    Args:
        url (str): The URL to the Youtube video
    Raises:
        selenium.common.exceptions.NoSuchElementException:
        When certain elements to look for cannot be found
    """
    comments = []
    tittle = ""
    # Note: replace argument with absolute path to the driver executable.
     #driver = webdriver.Chrome(ChromeDriverManager().install())
    #driver = webdriver.Chrome(executable_path=r"/Users/tsewangthilly/Downloads/chromedriver")
    #driver = webdriver.Chrome(executable_path=os.path.abspath("chromedriver.exe"))
    #driver = webdriver.Chrome()
    driver = webdriver.Chrome(ChromeDriverManager().install())

    # Navigates to the URL, maximizes the current window, and
    # then suspends execution for (at least) 5 seconds (this
    # gives time for the page to load).
    driver.get(url)
    driver.maximize_window()
    time.sleep(5)

    try:
        # Extract the elements storing the video title and
        # comment section.
        title = driver.find_element_by_xpath('//*[@id="container"]/h1/yt-formatted-string').text
        comment_section = driver.find_element_by_xpath('//*[@id="comments"]')
    except exceptions.NoSuchElementException:
        # Note: Youtube may have changed their HTML layouts for
        # videos, so raise an error for sanity sake in case the
        # elements provided cannot be found anymore.
        error = "Error: Double check selector OR "
        error += "element may not yet be on the screen at the time of the find operation"
        print(error)

    # Scroll into view the comment section, then allow some time
    # for everything to be loaded as necessary.
    driver.execute_script("arguments[0].scrollIntoView();", comment_section)
    time.sleep(7)

    # Scroll all the way down to the bottom in order to get all the
    # elements loaded (since Youtube dynamically loads them).
    last_height = driver.execute_script("return document.documentElement.scrollHeight")

    while True:
        # Scroll down 'til "next load".
        driver.execute_script("window.scrollTo(0, document.documentElement.scrollHeight);")

        # Wait to load everything thus far.
        time.sleep(2)

        # Calculate new scroll height and compare with last scroll height.
        new_height = driver.execute_script("return document.documentElement.scrollHeight")
        if new_height == last_height:
            break
        last_height = new_height

    # One last scroll just in case.
    driver.execute_script("window.scrollTo(0, document.documentElement.scrollHeight);")

    try:
        # Extract the elements storing the usernames and comments.
        username_elems = driver.find_elements_by_xpath('//*[@id="author-text"]')
        comment_elems = driver.find_elements_by_xpath('//*[@id="content-text"]')
    except exceptions.NoSuchElementException:
        error = "Error: Double check selector OR "
        error += "element may not yet be on the screen at the time of the find operation"
        print(error)

    print("> VIDEO TITLE: " + title + "\n")
    print("> USERNAMES & COMMENTS:")

    for username, comment in zip(username_elems, comment_elems):
        comments.append(comment.text)
        
    wordsAll.append(comments)
    titles.append(title)
    driver.close()

if __name__ == "__main__":
    scrape(sys.argv[1])

#getting the unique individual words using nltk and regex
wordsDf = []
i = 0
tokenizer = n.RegexpTokenizer(r"\w+'?\w+")
t = [[],['gingerbread', 'man'], ['woolly','rita','wolstencroft']]
for lst in wordsAll:
    words = []
    for sen in lst:
        new_words = tokenizer.tokenize(sen)
        for a in new_words:
            a = re.sub("\d+", "", a)
            if a == 'I' or a == 'A' or a == 'a' or len(a) > 1:
                words.append(np.char.lower(a))
    words.sort()
    words = pd.DataFrame(words, columns = ['words'])
    h = words['words'].value_counts()
    r = pd.DataFrame(h)
    r['k'] = r.index
    r.columns = ['count','word']
    if i < 3:
        r = r.drop(t[i])
    wordsDf.append(r)
    r.to_csv(str(i)+".csv", index = True)
    i = i +1

Testing! Statistically Significant?

Using a t test we check if most common 800 lemmas in fact predict 75% of daily words, we can clearly see none of the category predict 75% of the lemmas, but we can still check using t test that the data is the siginficatly different from 75%.

It is statistically lower than 75%!

In [358]:
# t test to predict if 75% of scapped lemma matches most common 800 words 
tset, pval = ttest_1samp(per2, 0.75)
print(pval)

if pval < 0.05 :
    print(" we are rejecting null hypothesis")
else:
    print("we are accepting null hypothesis")

t = ['gingerbread', 'man','woolly','rita','wolstencroft']
for lst in wordsAll:
    for sen in lst:
        new_words = tokenizer.tokenize(sen)
        for a in new_words:

                words.append(np.char.lower(a))
words.sort()
words = pd.DataFrame(words, columns = ['words'])
h = words['words'].value_counts()
r = pd.DataFrame(h)
r['k'] = r.index
r.columns = ['count','word']
r = r.drop(t)

    per2.append(float(x)/float(x+y)) 
    
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (3,3)
for a in range(0,12): 
    print(titles[a])
    i = per2[a]*100
    plt.pie([i,100-i], labels = ['perdicted '+str(i)+ "%",'fail to predict '+str(100-i)+ "%"]) 
    plt.show()
